      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Increasing the minimum wage typically forces small businesses in rural areas to either slim their profit margins or absorb the higher labor costs entirely. To survive, you may need to raise prices, reduce staff hours, or invest more heavily in efficiency tools, which are often costlier in remote locations. Many rural enterprises face greater strain because they have less customer diversity than city shops and rely heavily on labor-intensive operations. Despite your lower local costs, a significant pay hike still represents a powerful financial drain that small shops often cannot absorb.",
